item.title: Venezuela's Power Grid Afflicted by Brain Drain, Corruption
item.description: Hundreds of technicians have fled the country, leaving state electricity company Corpoelec badly in need of qualified professionals. Paired with corruption and a lack of maintenance, that means blackouts will only increase in number and length unless tens of billions of dollars in investments are made.

item.title: Ethiopian Airlines Black Boxes Showed 'Clear Similarities' With Lion Air Crash
item.description: Data from the black boxes of a crashed Ethiopian Airlines plane showed similarities to that from the Lion Air flight that crashed in October, Ethiopia’s transport minister said, adding to the pressure on aircraft maker Boeing.

item.title: Greece, Spain Raise Minimum Wage Despite High Unemployment
item.description: The left-wing governments of Greece and Spain are banking on an unorthodox strategy ahead of elections: raising the minimum wage despite high unemployment.

item.title: Trump's View of White Nationalism Sparks Political Debate
item.description: White House officials and Democrats traded shots over President Trump’s response to the New Zealand mosque massacre days after the president downplayed the role played by white nationalism.

item.title: New Zealand Shooter Likely Acted Alone, Police Say
item.description: The mass shooting of worshipers at two New Zealand mosques is increasingly being viewed as a lone-wolf attack. The shooter was active for more than half an hour, police said, in their first official timeline of the massacre that left 50 people dead.

item.title: Iran Sentences an American Citizen, a Navy Veteran, to 10 Years in Prison
item.description: Iranian authorities handed down a 10-year prison sentence to U.S. Navy veteran Michael White, who has been held since last July, his attorney said Saturday.

item.title: Yellow-Vest Protests Persist in Paris Despite Macron Outreach
item.description: Clashes erupted between police and demonstrators on the 18th-straight Saturday of yellow-vest protests in Paris.
